    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.31-32a_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">31</fw>
                
                <note type="curatorial">47 Neihardt Collection</note>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <note>pm. April 20, 1958</note>
                        Kirkwood, Mo.
                        10120 Manchester Rd.
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Treasured, noble friends of ours!</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I'm deeply greived that I should be writing to you on such an occasion &#8212; dear, lovable Monna<sic>Mona</sic>!</p>
                
                <p>There's only one thing that would have been worse, if her John had been taken from her. I don't think she could have taken it. It was justified, but never have I seen a wife with such adoration as Monna<sic>Mona</sic> had for her John. And she did have for <unclear>years</unclear> before <unclear>his</unclear> <unclear/> the knowledge that John was being honored, &amp; valued, they had together the comfort of a beautiful environment, &amp; how this beautiful woman valued everything she had, &amp; was grateful for it. I think &amp; hope she did not long have the trial of long illness or like myself the ordeal of limited sight &amp; hearing, which the years may bring. I can't read caligraphy<sic>calligraphy</sic>, not my own either &#8212; can merely follow a line.</p>
                
                <p>I make a try a newspapers sometimes after a denial of weeks, &amp; just happened to come upon the notice in the newspaper on one of these occasions. I knew it would be our blessed Monna's<sic>Mona's</sic> wish that you continue to be a brave example of living for all of us, &amp; try to be a good to <unclear/> John <unclear/>
                
                <pb facs="ni.j4a.26a.31-32a_0002"/>
                    
                <fw type="curatorial">32</fw>
                    
                    she is deprived of being. I'm convinced Erica &amp; Lindell will be most helpful to you now.</p>
                    
                <p>Together you &amp; dear Mona have raised a <unclear>rarely</unclear> fine family, helpful to everyone who knows them.</p>
                
                <p>I didn't send Easter <unclear>cards</unclear> to Erica &amp; Lindell, <unclear>Margaret</unclear> did not <unclear>wish me</unclear> to give the strain of my eyes <unclear/> the <unclear/> <unclear>confusion</unclear>.</p>
                
                <p>I don't think I can come to the Writers Conference, but will greatly miss seeing you, &amp; other dear friends.</p>
                
                <p>I <unclear>sorrow</unclear> for &amp; with you, but am grateful for <add>what</add> dear Mona did for me &amp; <unclear>that</unclear> I knew such a woman &amp; loved her &#8212;</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Alice       (Lippmann</signed>
                </closer>
            
                <postscript>
                    <p>Margaret too is deeply grieved &#8212; but grateful in knowing of the beauty of <del>your</del> such a marriage as you acheived.</p>
                    
                    <p>Don't impose on yourself a letter, I know how painful such letters are, I will hear about you from my friend <unclear>Helen Neal</unclear></p>
                    
                    <p>Deeply felt wishes for the dear family, from both of us.</p>
                </postscript>
            
            </div1>
            
            
